ional name from either of two places in Normandy called Fourneaux ‘(the) furnaces’, one in Manche, the other in Calvados. Compare   Furnace   and   Furnell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Furney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Furneaux  . It may sometimes have been confused with   Furness  ; the two names have variants in common (see   Furnace  )."]},{"name":"Fornell","meanings":["English: variant of   Furneaux  , or a nickname from Middle English <i>fornel</i> ‘small oven or furnace’."]},{"name":"Furnace","meanings":["English:","(Cumbria and Durham): variant of   Furness  .","(of Norman origin): sometimes a variant of   Furneaux  ."]},{"name":"Furnell","meanings":["English:","variant of   Furneaux  .","alternatively, perhaps a variant of   Farnell  . Compare   Funnell  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Furneaux was born in 1383, her father, John Furneaux, was 59 and her mother, Isolde Mountjoy, was 66. She married John Woodhouse in 1400. They were the parents of at least 5 sons and 3 daughters. She died about 1447, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1383–Abt 1447":"1383–umbes 1447","1383–1447":"1383–1447","1375–1431":"137